{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477864"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:06:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:06:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14898"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14898"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.76,0.02,0.02,0.16,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7589"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111760"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7589"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14898"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93828"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1643"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3730"},{"type":"tags","id":"3764"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18577"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33285"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45496"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45500"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111760"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of increasing fatigue, bone pain, and easy bruising. His parent reports he has become increasingly irritable and is refusing to walk. He has also developed noisy breathing and mild shortness of breath over the past week. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears pale and distressed. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. There are scattered bruises on his arms and legs, and petechiae on his trunk. There is tenderness over his long bones. No lymphadenopathy or hepatosplenomegaly is detected. Chest X-ray reveals a large anterior mediastinal mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial blood results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 75 g/L (110-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 45 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 12 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils 0.6 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (2.0-7.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia","Chronic lymphocytic leukaemia","Chronic myeloid leukaemia","Acute myeloid leukaemia","Acute promyelocytic leukaemia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with classic features of acute leukaemia including bone marrow failure (fatigue, bruising, fever) and characteristic blood count abnormalities showing pancytopaenia with a markedly elevated white cell count. The presence of bone pain, refusal to walk, and particularly the anterior mediastinal mass are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute lymphoblastic leukaemia (ALL)\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the most common childhood cancer. The presence of a mediastinal mass is particularly important as it is seen in up to 50% of ALL cases but is rare in other forms of acute leukaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic lymphocytic leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is a disease of older adults (typically \u0026gt;60 years) characterised by a gradual accumulation of mature-appearing lymphocytes. It would be extremely rare in a child and typically has a more indolent course.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic myeloid leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is also rare in children and typically presents with massive splenomegaly and a much higher white cell count (often \u0026gt;100 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L) with a predominance of mature granulocytes rather than blasts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute myeloid leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E (AML) can present similarly to ALL in children but is much less common in this age group and rarely presents with a mediastinal mass. The definitive distinction would be made by bone marrow examination and immunophenotyping of the blast cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute promyelocytic leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is a subtype of AML that typically presents with severe coagulopathy and disseminated intravascular coagulation. It is rare in children and would not typically present with a mediastinal mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of ALL would be confirmed with bone marrow aspiration and biopsy, which would show lymphoblasts. Immunophenotyping would determine the specific subtype of ALL, which has important prognostic and therapeutic implications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia is the most common childhood cancer, typically presenting between ages 2-5 years.","The classic triad of pallor, bruising and bone pain should raise suspicion for acute leukaemia in children.","A mediastinal mass in conjunction with pancytopaenia and circulating blasts is highly suggestive of acute lymphoblastic leukaemia."],"references":["Pagliaro L, Chen SJ, Herranz D, et al. Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2024;10(1):41. Published 2024 Jun 13. doi:10.1038/s41572-024-00525-x Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41572-024-00525-x"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93828"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14898"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93828"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-19T18:40:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-19T18:41:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7589"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111760"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type